<LEADPARA>  Mark Langston will not be the American League's starting pitcher tonight at
the SkyDome, which is just fine with him. After what he went through last
year, just being an All-Star is enough.;    The former San Jose State pitcher
signed a five-year, $16-million contract to join the California Angels for the
1990 season. He went 10-17, and although the Angels scored only 18 runs in
those losses, he was seen as another free-agent flop.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AFTER BEING LABELED A BUST, LANGSTON ENJOYS
BOOM YEAR  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  All-Star Game Preview  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     After this half-season, <PERSON>Langston</PERSON> has begun to justify the expenditure. He
is 12-3, winning two more games than he ever had by an All-Star break. He has
pitched into the seventh inning or later in 15 of his past 17 starts and has
teamed with <PERSON>Chuck Finley</PERSON> to lead <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> into contention. Why the dramatic
change?;    "Just having a very good team to play for has helped," <PERSON>Langston</PERSON>
said <DATE>Monday</DATE>. "We have a different team than last year. We have <PERSON>Dave Winfield</PERSON>
for a whole year, <PERSON>Wally Joyner</PERSON> is healthy and doing well, and we picked up
<PERSON>Gary Gaetti</PERSON> at third base.;    "Defensively, we're extremely sound. We have
the bats to keep us close, and the bullpen, with (All-Star teammate) <PERSON>Bryan
Harvey</PERSON>, has been outstanding. That's all helped.";    <PERSON>Langston</PERSON> spent most of
his career as a bright spot on a bad <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> team. He made the All-Star team
in <DATE>1987</DATE>, finishing that season with 262 strikeouts in 272 innings. He was
traded to <LOCATION>Montreal</LOCATION> in <DATE>May 1989</DATE> for <PERSON>Randy Johnson</PERSON>, <PERSON>Brian Holman</PERSON> and <PERSON>Gene
Harris</PERSON>, and he bolted for big money and a big market after that season.;   
<PERSON>Langston</PERSON> began his Angels career by teaming with <PERSON>Mike Witt</PERSON> to throw a
no-hitter, but it went all downhill from there. "I lost four games in a row,
2-1," he said. "Then I got beat around pretty badly and lost confidence. I had
made my living being an offensive, aggressive pitcher, and I lost that. I
tried to pick my spots, and I fell behind in counts.";    Through it all,
<PERSON>Langston</PERSON> never threw so much as a tantrum. He never kicked a water cooler. "To
me, he's an All-Star two years in a row," Angels Manager <PERSON>Doug Rader</PERSON> said. "Not
necessarily from a performance standpoint, but from a character standpoint."; 
  Longtime rival <PERSON>Kirby Puckett</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION> said of Langston: "There's nothing
any different about him that I've seen. You just try to make him get the ball
down.";    <PERSON>Langston</PERSON> and <PERSON>Finley</PERSON> each have 12 victories, tying <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Scott
Erickson</PERSON> for the league lead. At this rate, <PERSON>Langston</PERSON> could have his first
20-win season. He won 19 games in <DATE>'87</DATE>, a <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> record.;    "You can win 30
games, but if your team doesn't get into the playoffs, it doesn't really
matter," he said. "I felt I had a legitimate chance with <LOCATION>Montreal</LOCATION>. We were in
first for 2 1/2 months before folding, and I still think we had the best team.
Now, even though it's a tough division, we're in a very good position.";   
<PERSON>Langston</PERSON> has come a long way in a season, and a long way since he left defunct
Buchser High School in <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION>. He was offered plenty of soccer
scholarships, but there was not much interest in him as a baseball player. His
heart said baseball, and he said <DATE>Monday</DATE> with a rich man's grin, "It was the
right decision.";    "I had a good time at <LOCATION>San Jose State</LOCATION>," he said. "The main
thing there was just that the competition was up a little bit. It was a lot of
fun, and it sent me on my way."  </TEXT>
