<DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; GAME; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The California Angels think Mark Langston, the left-hander they signed to a
five-year, $16 million contract last year, is going to bounce back strongly
from his 17-loss season in 1990.;    So does Langston.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LANGSTON HELPS ANGELS TO SERIES SWEEP
HE PITCHES SIX SHUTOUT INNINGS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  A.L. ROUNDUP  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Langston took a step in that direction <DATE>Thursday</DATE> when he pitched six strong
innings in a 5-0 victory over his old team, the <ORGANIZATION>Seattle Mariners.</ORGANIZATION>;    The
victory allowed the Angels, an 80-82 team last season, to sweep the <ORGANIZATION>Mariners</ORGANIZATION>
in the season-opening, three-game series. It also gave the Angels their best
start since going 5-0 in <DATE>1970.</DATE>;    "He didn't doubt himself last year," Angels
Manager <PERSON>Doug Rader</PERSON> said of <LOCATION>Langston</LOCATION>. "It's important for anybody to get off to
a good start just simply because it's something to be proud. If he were going
to self destruct, it certainly would have been last year. It wouldn't have
been for an unsuccessful debut in <DATE>1991</DATE>.";    A year ago, <PERSON>Langston</PERSON> was one of
the biggest free-agent flops in baseball, going 10-17 with a 4.40 ERA. His
only highlight came in his debut, exactly a year ago, when he pitched seven
innings against <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> and combined with <PERSON>Mike Witt</PERSON> in the first of baseball's
record nine no-hitters.;    In <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s game, <PERSON>Dave Winfield</PERSON> drove in three
runs for the second straight game. He had a two-run double in the seventh.;   
"It takes a lot of pressure off of you when you've got the runs," <PERSON>Langston</PERSON>
said. "<PERSON>Dave</PERSON> had a really big hit. It gave us a really big lift.";    <PERSON>Langston</PERSON>
gave up a two-out single to <PERSON>Ken Griffey Jr.</PERSON> in the first inning and then
retired 13 straight <ORGANIZATION>Mariners</ORGANIZATION> before <PERSON>Dave Valle</PERSON> opened the sixth with a
single.;    <PERSON>Langston</PERSON> was lifted when the <ORGANIZATION>Mariners</ORGANIZATION> loaded the bases on singles
by <PERSON>Edgar Martinez</PERSON> and <PERSON>Griffey</PERSON> and a walk to <PERSON>Alvin Davis</PERSON>. But <PERSON>Jeff Robinson</PERSON>
came in and got the next three outs.;    <PERSON>Robinson</PERSON> got <PERSON>Jay Buhner</PERSON> to foul out
to first baseman <PERSON>Wally Joyner</PERSON>, <PERSON>Pete O'Brien</PERSON> to pop out to shortstop <PERSON>Dick
Schofield</PERSON> and struck out pinch hitter <PERSON>Greg Briley</PERSON>. He retired the <ORGANIZATION>Mariners</ORGANIZATION> in
order in the eighth and ninth for a save.;    "You can't read too much this
early," <PERSON>Langston</PERSON> said. "But it's very encouraging. It's outstanding to be able
to come in here and take three from probably their three best pitchers.";
INDIANS 6, RED SOX 4: <PERSON>Brook Jacoby</PERSON> drove in three runs and <LOCATION>Cleveland</LOCATION> spoiled
<PERSON>Danny Darwin</PERSON>'s debut in <LOCATION>Boston.</LOCATION>;    <PERSON>Eric King</PERSON> blanked <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION> on three hits
over six innings before tiring and needing relief help in a three-run seventh.
<PERSON>Doug Jones</PERSON> pitched the ninth for his second save.;    <ORGANIZATION>Darwin</ORGANIZATION>, signed for <MONEY>$11.8
million</MONEY> as a free agent after leading the <ORGANIZATION>National League</ORGANIZATION> in ERA last season
for <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, was unimpressive in his first start for the Red Sox.;    The
Indians rocked <PERSON>Darwin</PERSON> for three runs in the first inning and added three more
in the second, the last two coming on <PERSON>Jacoby</PERSON>'s wind-blown triple off reliever
<PERSON>Tom Bolton.</PERSON>; BLUE JAYS 7, BREWERS 3: Off-season acquisitions <PERSON>Devon White</PERSON> and
<PERSON>Joe Carter</PERSON> continued to spark the offense and <PERSON>David Wells</PERSON> pitched eight strong
innings as host <LOCATION>Toronto</LOCATION> beat Milwaukee.;    <PERSON>Carter</PERSON>, acquired from <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION>,
drove in two runs, giving him five in four games while batting .400 for the
<ORGANIZATION>Blue Jays</ORGANIZATION>. White, traded by <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>, went 3 for 5 and scored three runs,
giving him five for the season to go with a .389 average.;    <PERSON>Wells</PERSON> (1-0), who
has never pitched a complete game in 28 career starts, allowed three runs on
eight hits, struck out two and walked one.; TIGERS 11, YANKEES 5: <PERSON>Cecil
Fielder</PERSON> drove in three runs and scored four times as <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION> beat visiting <LOCATION>New
York.</LOCATION>;    <PERSON>Travis Fryman</PERSON> also had three RBIs for <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Roberto Kelly</PERSON>
drove in a career-high five runs for the Yankees.;    Fielder, who led the
majors last season with 51 homers and 132 RBIs, singled home two runs in the
seventh and drove in another with a fielder's choice grounder in the eighth.  </TEXT>
