<TEXT>
<P>
MARK LANGSTON 
</P>
<P>
Age: 29 
</P>
<P>
Position: Pitcher 
</P>
<P>
Major league experience: Six years 
</P>
<P>
How obtained: Signed as free agent, <DATE>Dec. 8, 1989</DATE>. 
</P>
<P>
Pertinent stats: Went a combined 16-14 in <DATE>1989</DATE> with <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Montreal</LOCATION>. 
</P>
<P>
Led the <ORGANIZATION>American League</ORGANIZATION> in strikeouts in <DATE>1984</DATE>, <DATE>1986</DATE> and <DATE>1987</DATE>. Signed a 
five-year, <MONEY>$16-million</MONEY> contract with the Angels. 
</P>
<P>
Comments: Considered baseball's premier free agent last <DATE>fall</DATE>, <PERSON>Langston</PERSON>'s 
presence has given the Angels a surplus of quality starters. The left-hander is 
best known for his fastball, which has helped him strike out at least 200 in 
five of the last six seasons, but he also can be effective with a variety of 
breaking and offspeed pitches. Langston has had a tendency to give up the long 
ball -- he allowed 30 or more home runs a season from 1986-88 -- but many came 
inside <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION>'s cozy <LOCATION>Kingdome</LOCATION>. His earned-run average has improved in each of 
the last four seasons, from 5.47 to 4.85, 3.84, 3.34 and 2.74, and he has 
proven a durable commodity. He has been on the disabled list just once in six 
years. 
</P></TEXT>
