<P>
THE NEGRO SPEAKS OF RIVERS BY LANGSTON HUGHES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I've known rivers: 
</P>
<P>
I've known rivers ancient as the world and older than the 
</P>
<P>
flow of human blood in human veins. 
</P>
<P>
My soul has grown deep like the rivers. 
</P>
<P>
I bathed in the <LOCATION>Euphrates</LOCATION> when dawns were young. 
</P>
<P>
I built my hut near the <LOCATION>Congo</LOCATION> and it lulled me to sleep. 
</P>
<P>
I looked upon the <ORGANIZATION>Nile</ORGANIZATION> and raised the pyramids above it. 
</P>
<P>
I heard the singing of the <LOCATION>Mississippi</LOCATION> when Abe Lincoln 
</P>
<P>
went down to <LOCATION>New Orleans</LOCATION>, and I've seen its muddy 
</P>
<P>
bosom turn all golden in the sunset. 
</P>
<P>
I've known rivers: 
</P>
<P>
Ancient, dusky rivers. 
</P>
<P>
My soul has grown deep like the rivers. 
</P>
<P>
From "Selected Poems of <PERSON>Langston Hughes</PERSON>," an edition published this month by 
Vintage Classics (<MONEY>$9.95</MONEY>, paper; 297 pp.). The <DATE>1926</DATE> publication of <PERSON>Hughes</PERSON>' first 
book of poems, "The Weary Blues," launched a renaissance in black writing in 
<LOCATION>America</LOCATION>. copyright <DATE>1959</DATE> by <PERSON>Langston Hughes</PERSON>. Reprinted by permission of the 
publisher. 
</P></TEXT>
