<LEADPARA>  Mark Langston gained his 14th victory with the help of Wally Joyner's two-run
homer and RBI single Friday night as the visiting California Angels beat the
New York Yankees 5-1.;    Langston (14-4) gave up seven hits, including
Hensley Meulens' homer in the seventh, before needing last-out relief help
from Bryan Harvey, who earned his 24th save.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LANGSTON RECORDS 14TH WIN  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  A.L. Roundup  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Langston tied <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Scott Erickson</PERSON> for most wins in the American
League.; TIGERS 3, RANGERS 2: <PERSON>Scott Livingstone</PERSON>, playing in his first pro game
in his hometown, singled home the winning run in the 10th off <PERSON>Jeff Russell</PERSON> to
give <LOCATION>Detroit</LOCATION> the victory over error-plagued <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Arlington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas.</LOCATION>;   
<PERSON>Tony Phillips</PERSON> led off the 10th with a sinking liner to center that <PERSON>Gary Pettis</PERSON>
dropped for a two-base error. On the second pitch to <PERSON>Livingstone</PERSON>, catcher <PERSON>Ivan
Rodriguez</PERSON> fired a pickoff throw but the ball went into center field before
shortstop <PERSON>Mario Diaz</PERSON> could get to the base, and <PERSON>Phillips</PERSON> advanced to third on
<PERSON>Rodriguez</PERSON>'s second error of the game.;    Then <PERSON>Livingstone</PERSON> slapped a 1-and-1
pitch to left to score the run.; BLUE JAYS 6, ROYALS 5: Third baseman <PERSON>Kevin
Seitzer</PERSON>'s error with the bases loaded in the 11th helped <LOCATION>Toronto</LOCATION> beat <LOCATION>Kansas
City</LOCATION> in front of 50,326 spectators, the largest crowd in Blue Jays history.;
TWINS 6, BREWERS 3: In <LOCATION>Minneapolis</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Dan Gladden</PERSON>'s three-run double in the
eighth inning helped <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION> hand <LOCATION>Milwaukee</LOCATION> its fifth straight loss.;
MARINERS 7, INDIANS 4: <PERSON>Alonzo Powell</PERSON> hit a two-run homer in the second inning
and <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> scored four runs on five straight hits in the third as the
visiting Mariners beat Cleveland.; ETC.: The game between the <ORGANIZATION>Chicago White
Sox</ORGANIZATION> and host <ORGANIZATION>Boston Red Sox</ORGANIZATION> was postponed by rain and rescheduled as part of a
day-night doubleheader today.  </TEXT>
